<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12191c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12191c">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12191c"> 191(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> in severalty</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[We]</font> find in England and in those parts of Ireland colonised by the Norman invaders a system of dual ownership, all land being held on the ultimate title of a grant from the King; a personal and contractual relationship between vassal and lord, tenant and landlord: ownership <mark>in severalty</mark>, the inheritance passing undivided to the eldest son: and differences of social status depending not on blood, but, if we look at realities, on wealth, since there is no legal barrier to a passage from one point in the social scale to another. <small> W.F. Butler, &ldquo;Irish Land Tenures&rdquo; <a name="IRLT" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#IRLT"><cite title="source">Studies</cite></a> (June 1924) 305</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Severalty: land held by an individual not joined with other owners.  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c12189c" href="c12all.htm#c12189c">VI.C.12:189(c)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
